Please, you can take from here.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:47.640
OK.

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:49.350
Thanks.

00:00:49.350 --> 00:00:50.310
OK.

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:51.720
So last week we--

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:58.560
last Thursday, we talked
about the basic concepts

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.310
in the practice of
short-range transit planning,

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:07.500
the level of service guidelines
and performance measures that

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:09.300
could actually be
defined and used

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:14.040
for the practice,
particularly related

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:20.460
to excess distances,
services span, maximum load,

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:22.140
convenience, and
comfort measures.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:26.460
Today, we will talk
a little bit more

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:31.830
about guidelines and standards
related to reliability,

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:36.210
and then we will talk about
some of the useful performance

00:01:36.210 --> 00:01:40.812
measures that could be
defined and measured

00:01:40.812 --> 00:01:43.020
for transit service.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:47.880
And then we will talk
about the actual procedure

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:55.530
of short-range planning for some
of the agencies from which we

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:56.820
have some examples.

00:01:56.820 --> 00:02:00.360
And then we will talk about
some of the caveats that

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:04.900
could actually be
identified for those.

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:11.940
So let's start with guidelines
and with the standards related

00:02:11.940 --> 00:02:14.650
to reliability first.

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:21.060
So in terms of reliability, as
we briefly discussed last week,

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:23.640
most agencies have
formal procedures

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:28.455
for monitoring service delivery
focusing on time performance.

00:02:28.455 --> 00:02:30.420
The on-time
performance is usually

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:35.250
considered to be zero minutes
early and up to five minutes

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:36.000
late.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:42.270
As we discussed, early arrivals
is not considered on-time.

00:02:42.270 --> 00:02:49.320
That could be because early
departures basically are not

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:53.040
considered on-time because
early departures could actually

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:57.150
have a more negative
impact on travel time.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:03:01.020
And the other possible
reason is that it's probably

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:04.080
early departures
are easier to avoid.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:09.900
When you compare later
arrivals or later departures,

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:12.060
possible reasons
that could actually

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:14.580
contribute to a
late arrival could

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:18.360
be the vehicle getting stuck
in traffic, congestion,

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:26.220
or due to high load and high
dwell times, which is usually

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:28.350
difficult to avoid.

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:35.070
But when it comes to early
arrivals and early departures,

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:41.520
the driver could actually slow
down in the upstream segments

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:47.190
to make sure that the
arrival is kind of on time.

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:52.380
So about 2/3 of agencies--
there are different thresholds

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:56.010
that are defined in terms
of acceptable thresholds

00:03:56.010 --> 00:04:03.030
for the percentage of arrivals
within this tolerance interval

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:07.140
from zero to five minutes late.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:12.180
However, the usual practice
is that about 2/3 of agencies

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:16.769
report on rush hour, on-time
performances of 90% and above.

00:04:16.769 --> 00:04:22.740
But in practice, this threshold
ranges between 80%, 85%,

00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:25.830
up to 90%, 98%, depending
on the mode of the service

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:32.100
and depending on the situation,
how the congestion level is,

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:37.950
how the load in the network
is, if there is right of way,

00:04:37.950 --> 00:04:43.800
like separated right of way for
that transit service or not.

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:48.150
So it is written somehow
as specific to the system,

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:53.580
but 90% is basically the
threshold that 2/3 of agencies

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:57.540
basically accept.

00:04:57.540 --> 00:05:00.960
Most agencies also keep
track and keep route level

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:03.690
information on
passenger complaints

00:05:03.690 --> 00:05:09.710
that could relate to
on-time or late arrivals.

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:13.560
It could relate also
to denial to board

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:16.410
or to the crowding situation.

00:05:16.410 --> 00:05:22.650
They would also keep
track and keep information

00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:25.830
on missed trips and
accidents and interruptions

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:30.540
and disruptions, basically.

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.000
So when it comes to
reliability, there

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.570
is a need to explain this.

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:39.210
I briefly mentioned
this last week,

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:40.910
that the services,
the transit service

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:45.250
is basically classified
into two types.

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:49.860
One is walk-up service, which
is related to higher frequency

00:05:49.860 --> 00:05:52.890
service that is
usually schedule-free

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:55.800
and/or headway-based.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:58.650
Typically with a service
that is with headway

00:05:58.650 --> 00:06:03.570
less than 10 minutes or some
say less than 15 minutes,

00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:06.060
it's considered to
be walk-up service.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:09.390
For example, the T service
in the central area of Boston

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.960
would be considered
a walk-up service.

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:15.150
BRT systems are
also, some of them

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:19.170
are schedule-free and
could be considered walk-up

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:22.440
or basically, headway-based.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:24.270
Performance measures
that are related

00:06:24.270 --> 00:06:28.410
to reliability for walk-up
service is based on headway,

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:32.190
and it basically measures
the regularity of headways.

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:35.940
As opposed to service, which
is scheduled that's basically

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:41.190
based on published timetables
and published schedule

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:45.990
and delivered based on
that, basically that's

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:49.300
the service that is
usually for longer headway.

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:52.230
Headway is longer than 10
minutes, 10, 15 minutes.

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:55.170
And the performance measure
related to this service

00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:58.980
is usually being done
or being measured

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:02.820
based on punctuality of
service, being late or early.

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:10.450
So again, a trip is
considered on time

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:13.930
at each time point
along the route

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:17.020
and on the performance
window, basically.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:20.260
So usually, transit
agencies, for each route

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:22.900
they define certain
time points, which

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:27.760
could be major stops or
stations but usually, they

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:29.170
are less frequent.

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:31.750
I mean every three
or four stops,

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:33.940
there could be one
time point that you

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:38.980
measure the on-time arrivals and
on-time departures from there.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:43.330
You may have noticed, if
you're on a certain bus,

00:07:43.330 --> 00:07:45.100
this is my personal
experience, when I

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.670
lived in Brisbane in Australia.

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:52.450
There were some routes
that at some time when

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:57.970
you see that the bus is early,
the driver could actually

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.320
really slow down
before certain points,

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.010
and you could tell where
exactly the time point is

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:06.010
that the driver is
trying to basically make

00:08:06.010 --> 00:08:09.010
an on-time arrival
to those time points.

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:13.090
So arrivals are
measured at these time

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:15.920
points along the route.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:16.420
Right.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:27.440
So what are the actual
standards and actual tolerance

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:31.820
or thresholds that agencies
consider for service

00:08:31.820 --> 00:08:33.590
reliability measures?

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:37.530
One example is here from MBTA.

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:40.549
MBTA, actually for
walk-up service,

00:08:40.549 --> 00:08:45.700
which is the case for
most of the T service,

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:49.450
it allows basically
actual headway

00:08:49.450 --> 00:08:53.620
of up to 1.5 times
the scheduled headway

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:56.200
at origins and at time points.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:59.560
And then at
destinations, it also

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:02.470
defines another measure that
deals with the schedule's

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:03.460
running time.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:05.710
So basically,
there are two hooks

00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:10.060
that it kind of measures
the service based on those.

00:09:10.060 --> 00:09:12.550
One is the regularity
of service.

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:17.530
It doesn't allow or it
wants to measure cases

00:09:17.530 --> 00:09:22.420
where headway is longer than
expected, like 1.5 times

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.010
the scheduled headway.

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:27.640
And the other constraint is
that the actual running time

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:31.840
is between 0.8 and 1.2 of
the scheduled running time.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.530
So when it comes
to actual headway,

00:09:38.530 --> 00:09:41.410
you can see that there
is no lower bound

00:09:41.410 --> 00:09:42.940
to the actual headway.

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:46.030
Does anyone have any comments
why there is no actual lower

00:09:46.030 --> 00:09:46.660
bound here?

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:53.450
Yeah, please.

00:09:53.450 --> 00:09:55.740
AUDIENCE: Lower than
scheduled headway just means

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:58.910
that there's more service.

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:01.660
And if that leaves a
gap somewhere else,

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:04.560
then that would be
record-- that would

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.567
count for over the schedule.

00:10:07.567 --> 00:10:08.400
NEEMA NASSIR: Right.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:08.900
Yeah.

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:12.690
Given that the number of trips
are constant during the day,

00:10:12.690 --> 00:10:18.120
if you guarantee that there
is a maximum headway, then

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:19.620
on the other hand,
you can kind of

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:25.360
guarantee that headway
is not too short there.

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:27.670
However, when it comes
to scheduled service,

00:10:27.670 --> 00:10:34.290
then there is constraints on
early and late departures,

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:35.140
basically.

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:42.430
So at origins, what MBTA
considers, at origin terminus,

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:45.700
considers on-time departures
between zero and three

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:48.730
minutes, zero minutes early
and three minutes late.

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:50.890
And then at time
points, it allows up

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:53.620
to seven minutes late.

00:10:53.620 --> 00:10:56.920
Does anyone have any comments
about the difference?

00:10:56.920 --> 00:11:03.190
Why does it allow
less late departures

00:11:03.190 --> 00:11:04.150
at the origin terminus?

00:11:07.348 --> 00:11:11.212
AUDIENCE: Give us control
at the intermediary terminus

00:11:11.212 --> 00:11:13.160
[INAUDIBLE] at the terminal.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:14.210
NEEMA NASSIR: Yeah.

00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:18.170
That could be the case.

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:23.960
or to put it the other
way, transit agencies,

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:27.000
when they schedule these
trips and they schedule

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.460
these vehicles, they
allow a recovery time

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:36.920
between the end of one trip and
the beginning of the next trip.

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:39.320
And that actually
is there to kind

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:44.390
of help with
punctuality of service,

00:11:44.390 --> 00:11:51.340
and therefore, it does allow
less tolerance on delay

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:52.250
at the beginning.

00:11:52.250 --> 00:11:56.780
But when it goes
along the route, when

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:59.150
bus goes along the
route, it kind of

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:02.860
gets out of control
as you mentioned.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:06.425
There are not really good
ways and good leverages

00:12:06.425 --> 00:12:12.890
to allow buffer to
the running time.

00:12:12.890 --> 00:12:16.420
And then at the
destination, it's basically,

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:19.330
MBTA allows up to
three minutes early

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:23.890
and five minutes late
it should be obvious

00:12:23.890 --> 00:12:28.840
why it allows early arrivals
to destination because it's

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:33.010
the last stop, and we don't need
to worry about arriving early

00:12:33.010 --> 00:12:35.770
to the final destination.

00:12:35.770 --> 00:12:39.580
At the route level, there
is one other guideline

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:43.540
that, at the route level, 75%
of time points must be on time.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:49.870
So although for
the overall system,

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:54.200
the threshold here was in
the range of 90% or 95%,

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:56.770
or between 80%, 85%, and 95%.

00:12:56.770 --> 00:13:01.180
But at route level,
when you're looking

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:03.850
at the on-time arrivals,
it has to be larger

00:13:03.850 --> 00:13:08.020
than 75% of the time.

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:11.980
So what will happen
if it doesn't--

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:15.060
a certain route doesn't
meet this standard?

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:20.720
Is there any thoughts?

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:22.500
Oh, please.

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:25.420
AUDIENCE: You could shift
the schedule for that segment

00:13:25.420 --> 00:13:27.330
and republish it and add extra--

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:28.390
NEEMA NASSIR: Yeah.

00:13:28.390 --> 00:13:34.070
So you can increase,
basically, the running time

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:37.390
and make sure that you adjust
the schedule in a way that

00:13:37.390 --> 00:13:41.140
can be delivered punctually.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:43.910
So that's what's
explained in this slide.

00:13:43.910 --> 00:13:53.980
So if you observe in some of the
routes the performance in terms

00:13:53.980 --> 00:13:57.460
of punctuality is poor,
then you can take a look

00:13:57.460 --> 00:14:00.790
at the historical data and
historical performances

00:14:00.790 --> 00:14:06.850
in terms of running time,
revise the running time

00:14:06.850 --> 00:14:11.920
from terminus to terminus
and that will actually,

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:16.630
you can basically revise that to
be a mean of this distribution,

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.020
assuming that the travel
times, the running times

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:22.630
are distributed normally.

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:24.272
And go ahead, please.

00:14:24.272 --> 00:14:26.230
AUDIENCE: I mean, if it's
only a 5% probability

00:14:26.230 --> 00:14:29.360
that this will happen
but it happens actually

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:30.505
a lot more than that.

00:14:30.505 --> 00:14:33.227
It's probably a result
of another factor,

00:14:33.227 --> 00:14:37.435
like drivers or vehicles
or traffic or [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:37.435 --> 00:14:38.920
constructions [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:44.044 --> 00:14:45.960
NEEMA NASSIR: Well,
that's a good point, yeah.

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:49.410
So there may be,
for example, you

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:55.690
know when there is shared right
of way with background traffic,

00:14:55.690 --> 00:14:58.710
there's a lot of indeterminacy
in terms of travel time,

00:14:58.710 --> 00:15:01.710
especially if the
roadway is congested,

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:07.020
and that could be one possible
result for unreliability

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:08.340
of running time.

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:14.940
One possible thing that could
be done is like dedicated lanes

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:18.105
to the transit
and kind of trying

00:15:18.105 --> 00:15:23.450
to improve the performance
and match the schedule.

00:15:23.450 --> 00:15:25.320
So that could be one other way.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:29.400
But what I mentioned was that if
this is the last thing that we

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:32.940
can do and that we
cannot basically improve

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:37.860
the reliability of arrivals, we
may actually allow a little bit

00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:41.630
of buffer to the travel time.

00:15:41.630 --> 00:15:53.090
And that's not only by extending
the running time to a job

00:15:53.090 --> 00:15:55.120
that we can observe,
but also, you

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:58.820
can adjust the recovery
time between end

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:03.400
of one trip to the next trip
to the chosen amount that

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:09.370
makes sure that a certain
confidence can actually

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:13.030
be gained in terms of on-time
performance of next trip.

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:18.160
In terms of the actual
objective that TransLink

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:21.790
has in place for
reliability, again depending

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:26.020
on different modes,
TransLink defines

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:34.757
different acceptance thresholds
for given on-time definitions.

00:16:34.757 --> 00:16:36.340
And on-time definitions
could actually

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:43.000
vary as well as a level of
compliance or the acceptance

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.380
threshold.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:48.140
So is there any
questions about this?

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:48.710
Any comments?

00:16:55.370 --> 00:17:04.630
So there are some more
detail measures and event

00:17:04.630 --> 00:17:11.319
measures for transit service.

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:15.619
It comes to variables that
are related to transit service

00:17:15.619 --> 00:17:18.400
supply and demand side.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:22.569
Quantities actually
can be classified

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:25.089
into three different
groups, the quantities that

00:17:25.089 --> 00:17:28.150
are related to
the service input,

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:30.100
quantities related
to service output,

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:32.950
and quantities related
to service consumption.

00:17:32.950 --> 00:17:35.890
So service input is
basically the resources

00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:41.068
that the transit agency is
using to produce the service.

00:17:41.068 --> 00:17:45.730
Service output is basically
measuring the produced service.

00:17:45.730 --> 00:17:49.210
And service consumption
is how this service

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:52.450
is being consumed and
being appreciated and being

00:17:52.450 --> 00:17:55.160
used by the public.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:18:03.870
So different measures
can be defined

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:07.280
to measure the performance
of transit system

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:08.880
based on these quantities.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.280
For example, you can
look at only the vertices

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:20.420
of this triangle, like what is
the amount of labor, including

00:18:20.420 --> 00:18:22.490
drivers and maintenance?

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:27.080
What is the capital cost of
the fleet and infrastructure?

00:18:27.080 --> 00:18:31.850
What is the fuel
consumption in the system?

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:36.170
Or, on the other hand, you can
look at the service outputs.

00:18:36.170 --> 00:18:39.260
It would be like a
measure of the service

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:47.220
in terms of how much
service the system actually

00:18:47.220 --> 00:18:52.100
is producing in terms of vehicle
hours or revenue hours, vehicle

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:56.340
miles or revenue hours, capacity
miles and service reliability.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.710
And then consumption
of service, that

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:00.650
is dealing with
number of passengers,

00:19:00.650 --> 00:19:05.760
passenger miles, operating
revenue, and operating safety.

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:11.940
But you can go one level up
with playing with these measures

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:19.650
and compute, for example, the
ratios of these quantities.

00:19:19.650 --> 00:19:24.200
So each one of these
edges basically

00:19:24.200 --> 00:19:28.940
are dealing with the
ratio of one quantity

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:35.750
at one vertex as opposed to over
the quantity of the other one.

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:39.020
For example, what
we are basically--

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:41.180
efficiency measures
are basically

00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:43.850
dealing with how we
are doing in terms

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:49.190
of producing service as
given our available resources

00:19:49.190 --> 00:19:51.050
or the consumed resources.

00:19:51.050 --> 00:19:54.830
The service
effectiveness basically

00:19:54.830 --> 00:20:00.800
deals with how we are doing
in terms of giving service

00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:04.400
to public, moving public
and producing mobility

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:10.800
in the network over
the service that we

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:13.610
produce, how our service
is appreciated and used

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:14.870
and utilized.

00:20:14.870 --> 00:20:18.800
For example, a service that is
poorly designed, for example,

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:23.640
like every five
minute trips overnight

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:26.630
from a suburb to another
suburb, it's a service,

00:20:26.630 --> 00:20:32.780
and it has produced vehicle
hours and vehicle miles.

00:20:32.780 --> 00:20:34.620
It has consumed resources.

00:20:34.620 --> 00:20:36.440
However, it may
not be appreciated

00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:38.090
because it's poorly designed.

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:42.230
So that's the kind of
the role of measures

00:20:42.230 --> 00:20:45.050
that are related to
service effectiveness

00:20:45.050 --> 00:20:51.230
to take care of quality of
design and quality of service,

00:20:51.230 --> 00:20:53.330
basically.

00:20:53.330 --> 00:20:57.500
So and one other comment
about this triangle

00:20:57.500 --> 00:21:02.210
is that the cost
efficiency measures

00:21:02.210 --> 00:21:09.800
kind of dealing with the
quality of the planning

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:12.875
on the operational side,
operational planning.

00:21:12.875 --> 00:21:16.560
How the optimization and
how the tactical decisions

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:21.650
are made in terms of
producing the most service out

00:21:21.650 --> 00:21:23.430
of the existing resources.

00:21:23.430 --> 00:21:26.450
On the other hand,
the decisions that

00:21:26.450 --> 00:21:30.530
are related to service
planning could actually

00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:34.730
use measures that are related
to service effectiveness.

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:37.280
So in terms of
alternative measures,

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:43.740
like benefit and cost measures
that could be defined and used

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:49.110
for short-range
transit planning--

00:21:49.110 --> 00:21:52.440
before we go into discussion
of benefits and cost

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:56.790
for transit system, there is one
thing that I need to mention.

00:21:56.790 --> 00:21:59.000
What's happening
in transit system

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.420
is that they are usually not
run, as you know, for profit

00:22:03.420 --> 00:22:07.320
and that's probably one
of the main differences

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:10.290
between the business model of
a transit system as compared

00:22:10.290 --> 00:22:13.890
to other regular businesses,
where they make decisions

00:22:13.890 --> 00:22:20.850
based on profit and based on the
revenue over or benefit of cost

00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:23.130
or better benefit over cost.

00:22:23.130 --> 00:22:26.160
What happens in
transit agencies is

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:31.050
that it can be thought as a type
of benefit over cost analysis

00:22:31.050 --> 00:22:33.970
but the cost and benefit
is a little bit different.

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:40.150
The benefit is dealing with the
public service and the amount

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:45.730
of consumer surplus
or the social welfare

00:22:45.730 --> 00:22:49.360
that you can produce, the
mobility that you can produce.

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:52.510
On the other hand, the
cost could actually

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:57.220
include the operating cost and
also could include the revenue.

00:22:57.220 --> 00:23:01.850
It basically can be defined as
operating cost minus revenue.

00:23:01.850 --> 00:23:07.000
So when it comes to the
financial unit of benefit

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:11.440
and cost, the financial
unit includes both the cost

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:13.190
and revenue.

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:14.780
And then when it
comes to benefit,

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:17.840
what's usually being used
as a measure of benefit

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:21.170
is the service that
is being delivered

00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:28.970
in terms of the
social welfare measure

00:23:28.970 --> 00:23:34.740
or the mobility that actually
is produced in the network.

00:23:34.740 --> 00:23:39.020
So once we discuss some of
these alternative measures,

00:23:39.020 --> 00:23:41.935
it may be a little more clear.

00:23:41.935 --> 00:23:43.310
So one of the
measures that could

00:23:43.310 --> 00:23:49.250
be defined and really easy
probably to define and measure

00:23:49.250 --> 00:23:50.360
is the revenue.

00:23:50.360 --> 00:23:52.680
Like, what's the
fare box revenue?

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:54.020
What's the total?

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:56.810
The advantage that
this measure would have

00:23:56.810 --> 00:24:01.400
is that it's very relevant
to financial concerns.

00:24:01.400 --> 00:24:05.060
It actually, another
advantage that it has

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:08.240
is that it's related
to willingness to pay

00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:13.920
and it could be used as a
proxy of quality of service.

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:17.810
However, the disadvantage that
could be mentioned for revenue

00:24:17.810 --> 00:24:20.390
as a benefit measure
is that it discounts

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:24.050
value of reduced fare trips,
discounted trips, concession

00:24:24.050 --> 00:24:26.420
trips.

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:30.530
And it also has the disadvantage
that it favors higher income

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:32.090
passengers.

00:24:32.090 --> 00:24:38.550
So if we want to look
a little bit more

00:24:38.550 --> 00:24:41.220
closely at the nature
of transit service

00:24:41.220 --> 00:24:44.080
and what should be considered
as a benefit measure,

00:24:44.080 --> 00:24:47.196
we need to look at
the mobility and try

00:24:47.196 --> 00:24:52.890
to measure the mobility that has
been produced for the citizen,

00:24:52.890 --> 00:24:55.510
for the people living
in the network.

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:57.900
So we can count the
number of passengers

00:24:57.900 --> 00:25:02.190
who have used the system
and the advantage of this

00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:06.330
is that it reflects the
number of people who benefit

00:25:06.330 --> 00:25:10.490
and it basically values
each passenger equally.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:12.900
However, the
shortcoming of counting

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:17.250
only the number of
passengers is that it kind of

00:25:17.250 --> 00:25:19.290
doesn't reflect trip length.

00:25:22.790 --> 00:25:27.240
Not reflecting trip
length basically kind of

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:33.000
ignores an important component
in mobility, which deals

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:35.730
with access to opportunities.

00:25:35.730 --> 00:25:38.910
Which the access to
opportunities definitely cannot

00:25:38.910 --> 00:25:47.800
decrease with the
opportunities for mobility.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:49.930
And then the other
shortcoming is

00:25:49.930 --> 00:25:54.340
that it basically
reflects on link trips

00:25:54.340 --> 00:25:58.950
and not journeys or link trips.

00:25:58.950 --> 00:26:01.380
So you basically
double count passengers

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:06.270
who are making
transfers, although they

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:08.340
may be traveling
to one destination

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:10.980
and there's only one
opportunity at one destination

00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:14.550
or that will be actually
one activity happening

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:17.020
at the destination.

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:21.690
So one way to improve this
is to measure passenger miles

00:26:21.690 --> 00:26:25.200
as a better proxy of
mobility in the network.

00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:28.800
It has the advantage that
it weights longer trips more

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:37.080
and it's the best reflection of
benefits related to mobility.

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:38.680
Sorry about this.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:41.910
However, it's
hardest to measure.

00:26:41.910 --> 00:26:47.900
Does anyone have any idea,
comments about why it's hardest

00:26:47.900 --> 00:26:49.900
to measure?

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:56.330
Why is passenger miles in the
network hardest to measure?

00:26:56.330 --> 00:26:59.115
AUDIENCE: A lot of systems
don't have an exit.

00:26:59.115 --> 00:27:00.580
They only have an
entrance stile.

00:27:00.580 --> 00:27:01.750
NEEMA NASSIR: Exactly.

00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:06.760
So considering that we're
using the data for passenger,

00:27:06.760 --> 00:27:09.310
like from fare card
systems, many systems

00:27:09.310 --> 00:27:13.660
do not have the
requirements of tapping

00:27:13.660 --> 00:27:15.430
when you're exiting the system.

00:27:15.430 --> 00:27:17.390
So that's something
that is missing.

00:27:17.390 --> 00:27:20.560
So it requires some
sort of inference

00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:25.310
of highlighting our exit
locations to be able to measure

00:27:25.310 --> 00:27:26.680
the length of trip.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:29.590
However, and the
other disadvantage

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:34.180
is that it could find favor
higher income passengers.

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:36.340
So any comments about this?

00:27:36.340 --> 00:27:39.320
AUDIENCE: That assumes the
high-income passengers,

00:27:39.320 --> 00:27:42.803
that assumes higher income
people travel further.

00:27:42.803 --> 00:27:45.257
It's not necessarily the case.

00:27:45.257 --> 00:27:46.840
NEEMA NASSIR: Not
necessarily the case

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:54.820
but in systems where you have
distance-based fare structure,

00:27:54.820 --> 00:28:00.580
and when you basically have
the entrance and exits recorded

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:06.010
and you charge people by the
length or number of zones

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:09.700
that they have traveled,
that could be actually

00:28:09.700 --> 00:28:14.350
somehow favoring higher
income passengers

00:28:14.350 --> 00:28:17.650
because it is reasonable to
assume that higher income

00:28:17.650 --> 00:28:21.520
people are less
sensitive to the fare

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:26.110
and so their decisions
are basically

00:28:26.110 --> 00:28:28.470
kind of regardless of fare.

00:28:28.470 --> 00:28:30.080
So any comments?

00:28:35.554 --> 00:28:36.054
OK.

00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:44.170
So then on the cost
side, the measures that

00:28:44.170 --> 00:28:49.430
are dealing with
cost, the net cost

00:28:49.430 --> 00:28:53.900
is basically cost
of resources that

00:28:53.900 --> 00:29:00.770
are used to generate the
service minus the revenue.

00:29:00.770 --> 00:29:07.970
And it's usually most
directly constrained

00:29:07.970 --> 00:29:12.330
because that's exactly
the amount of money

00:29:12.330 --> 00:29:16.680
that you need to
secure for the service.

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:21.360
The budget actually goes
directly to the net cost.

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:23.980
So that's the advantage.

00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:27.373
However, the disadvantage is
that it's hardest to estimate.

00:29:30.710 --> 00:29:34.800
Any comments about why it
could be hardest to estimate as

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:35.625
compared to cost?

00:29:41.630 --> 00:29:47.930
At least for designs, for the
service that is not already

00:29:47.930 --> 00:29:54.500
in place, if you need
to estimate the revenue

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:59.420
and deduct that from cost
to generate net cost,

00:29:59.420 --> 00:30:02.030
it would be a
challenging thing to do,

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:06.890
to come up with estimates of
demand and predict the revenue.

00:30:06.890 --> 00:30:09.080
So that could be one
of the shortcomings

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:12.290
of net cost for designs.

00:30:12.290 --> 00:30:14.480
However, it may not
be that difficult when

00:30:14.480 --> 00:30:17.690
we are dealing with
the existing service

00:30:17.690 --> 00:30:21.350
because revenue is
basically already recorded

00:30:21.350 --> 00:30:24.610
by the fare box system.

00:30:24.610 --> 00:30:29.210
And then cost could be
another measure less directly

00:30:29.210 --> 00:30:36.170
constrained because actually,
we need to combine that

00:30:36.170 --> 00:30:37.910
with the revenue
to realize what's

00:30:37.910 --> 00:30:40.070
the net cost of the system?

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:43.160
Again, it could be
hard to estimate

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:48.260
but probably not as hard when
we compare it with net cost.

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:49.118
Go ahead.

00:30:49.118 --> 00:30:51.410
AUDIENCE: What is net cost?

00:30:51.410 --> 00:30:56.540
NEEMA NASSIR: Net cost is
basically cost of operation

00:30:56.540 --> 00:31:00.710
minus the revenue from fares.

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:04.730
And the reason that
it's tricky to measure

00:31:04.730 --> 00:31:09.833
is that the revenue side is
probably a little difficult

00:31:09.833 --> 00:31:10.815
to predict.

00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:21.630
So the next measure of cost
could be vehicle miles.

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:25.260
That basically deals with
the service that is produced.

00:31:25.260 --> 00:31:28.890
It's easy to measure
because you know number

00:31:28.890 --> 00:31:33.870
of trips that are delivered to
the system, and length of trips

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:34.380
are known.

00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:42.210
So vehicle miles is probably
the easiest measure to compute.

00:31:42.210 --> 00:31:44.490
But the disadvantage
is that they only

00:31:44.490 --> 00:31:49.890
reflect 3% of the cost
and that's probably

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:55.095
the part that is correlated
with fuel and with depreciation

00:31:55.095 --> 00:31:59.420
of the vehicles and
with maintenance.

00:31:59.420 --> 00:32:02.680
And then it also
penalizes fast service,

00:32:02.680 --> 00:32:09.350
not [AUDIO OUT] traveled
fast and on time

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:11.270
as opposed to the
model that is basically

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:16.940
delivered in congestion
and with long delays.

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:21.740
Another measure that is
probably a little bit more

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:26.120
closely reflecting our
cost is the vehicle hours.

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.370
And the vehicle miles
and vehicle hours

00:32:28.370 --> 00:32:33.290
are basically the revenue
miles and the revenue hours.

00:32:33.290 --> 00:32:37.106
What I mean by revenue,
that's basically the miles

00:32:37.106 --> 00:32:40.190
that these buses
and these vehicles

00:32:40.190 --> 00:32:44.960
have been in service from
the start of their trip

00:32:44.960 --> 00:32:46.490
to the end of the trip.

00:32:46.490 --> 00:32:54.960
There may be some trips,
like dead-ending trips,

00:32:54.960 --> 00:32:58.730
that the vehicle can
should go empty from one

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:02.930
location to another
location to the next trip,

00:33:02.930 --> 00:33:05.120
and those miles and
those vehicle hours

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:07.340
are not counted here.

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:11.180
So vehicle hours basically,
again, are easy to measure.

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:17.180
And the other advantage is that
it's related to more than 50%

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:20.870
of bus costs.

00:33:20.870 --> 00:33:27.440
It basically correlates
with the fuel consumption

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:32.720
and with driving
and operating cost.

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:39.530
So one of the cost
effectiveness measures

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:45.950
that MBTA uses for their system
and for their decision making

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:51.050
is basically net cost
per each passenger that

00:33:51.050 --> 00:33:53.690
is using the system.

00:33:53.690 --> 00:33:59.060
And then they usually define
this on a route basis.

00:33:59.060 --> 00:34:05.060
So the index I here could
be net cost per passenger

00:34:05.060 --> 00:34:10.449
for each route, and then it
shouldn't exceed three times

00:34:10.449 --> 00:34:16.350
the system-wide net
cost per passenger.

00:34:16.350 --> 00:34:21.739
So this is basically going back
to the triangle that we had.

00:34:21.739 --> 00:34:25.010
This is one of the measures that
is dealing with resources that

00:34:25.010 --> 00:34:27.679
are used to the
number of passengers

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:30.850
that are using the
service, regardless

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:32.080
of what the service was.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:41.310
So in terms of issues in
setting up a short-range transit

00:34:41.310 --> 00:34:49.800
planning process, this slide
mentions some of these issues,

00:34:49.800 --> 00:34:51.540
starting with the
roll-off budget

00:34:51.540 --> 00:34:54.870
constraints in the process
this could actually

00:34:54.870 --> 00:34:58.410
be related to before budget is
set and after budget is set.

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:02.400
Before budget is set,
there is some indeterminacy

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:08.520
in measuring the net
cost and basically

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:12.480
the budget that is requested in
the proposal for a new service

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:15.570
or for a change in the service.

00:35:15.570 --> 00:35:21.300
What's similar to any other
proposal that is usually done

00:35:21.300 --> 00:35:25.710
is that you try to find
the minimum possible budget

00:35:25.710 --> 00:35:30.740
that you're requesting for
what you're trying to deliver

00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:33.880
and that could be
a challenging task.

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:35.790
And then after
the budget is set,

00:35:35.790 --> 00:35:39.960
given all the indeterminacy
that was involved in predicting

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:47.850
the budget, then it's the issue
of optimizing the resources

00:35:47.850 --> 00:35:51.870
and optimizing the budget to
deliver and to gain the most

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:57.270
out of the existing resources.

00:35:57.270 --> 00:35:59.810
The other issue with--

00:35:59.810 --> 00:36:02.810
AUDIENCE: So in this
part of the process,

00:36:02.810 --> 00:36:06.970
I wonder if it should
be advisable to leave

00:36:06.970 --> 00:36:12.450
a margin of maneuver in respect
to budget constraints normally

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:16.890
you would have, even if you go
for the minimum possible to get

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:21.740
85%, 80%, out of that,
for political reasons

00:36:21.740 --> 00:36:24.870
or whatever reason there is.

00:36:24.870 --> 00:36:26.840
NEEMA NASSIR: Right.

00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:32.065
So that could actually make
the situation a little easier

00:36:32.065 --> 00:36:34.430
for people who are
involved in planning

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.440
and for the actual plans, right?

00:36:36.440 --> 00:36:43.880
So what Ricardo is
mentioning is there may be

00:36:43.880 --> 00:36:50.570
some buffers or some internal--

00:36:50.570 --> 00:36:56.150
some buffers in the budget
and some flexibility

00:36:56.150 --> 00:36:58.310
in the budget that
could actually

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:02.550
be allowed when you're
requesting the budget

00:37:02.550 --> 00:37:04.850
and when you're
delivering the budget,

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:08.390
delivering the service
that could actually

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:10.700
take care of some of
the indeterminacy that

00:37:10.700 --> 00:37:12.740
is involved in the
prediction of the budget

00:37:12.740 --> 00:37:13.970
and prediction of the costs.

00:37:18.090 --> 00:37:26.500
So the next, possibly
the next issue

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:31.600
that is involved in the
traditional or the existing

00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:34.630
practice for short-range
transit planning

00:37:34.630 --> 00:37:41.290
is that we kind of have a set
of standards and constraints

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:45.780
that gives us lower bounds on
some of the service measures.

00:37:45.780 --> 00:37:48.900
However, these
constraints only give us

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:52.320
an idea of what's the
feasible solution space.

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:56.370
It doesn't really tell us
what's the optimal design

00:37:56.370 --> 00:38:00.648
and how you can
basically optimize

00:38:00.648 --> 00:38:05.445
the allocation of resources
to improve the ridership.

00:38:05.445 --> 00:38:09.810
And that could
actually involve some

00:38:09.810 --> 00:38:12.570
of the art of the designers
and the art of people

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:15.870
who are involved in
identifying opportunities

00:38:15.870 --> 00:38:20.520
within the standards and within
the constraints and guidelines

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:23.400
to address the situation
and to gain the most

00:38:23.400 --> 00:38:28.420
out of the allocated resources.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:33.880
Then again, when it comes
to design of service,

00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:38.350
there is also this issue
between the existing

00:38:38.350 --> 00:38:44.515
service and proposals and
plans for additional service.

00:38:47.020 --> 00:38:52.030
As I mentioned last week,
the design of service

00:38:52.030 --> 00:38:53.640
is never from scratch.

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:59.500
There is always something
there for good reasons

00:38:59.500 --> 00:39:03.490
and you may want to predict
the existing service

00:39:03.490 --> 00:39:06.160
as much as possible
because people

00:39:06.160 --> 00:39:07.480
are relying on the service.

00:39:07.480 --> 00:39:15.310
They probably have formed
their travel habits and travel

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:17.740
attitudes based on
the existing service.

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:21.330
So changing these
services probably

00:39:21.330 --> 00:39:29.080
need to be really careful
and thoughtful, basically.

00:39:29.080 --> 00:39:35.170
However, when it comes to
addition of new service,

00:39:35.170 --> 00:39:40.330
we may want to make sure
that the new service

00:39:40.330 --> 00:39:46.150
kind of supports the
existing service effectively

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:51.760
and with all the overlaps
and all the misconnections

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:55.120
are identified in advance
and taken care of.

00:39:58.390 --> 00:40:01.240
Issue that we will eventually
talk about it later

00:40:01.240 --> 00:40:06.580
in another slide is that
some of existing practice

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:11.950
is dealing with short-range
transit planning decisions

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:16.720
dealing poorly
performing routes.

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:19.750
But the optimal
design is not always

00:40:19.750 --> 00:40:23.570
dealing with changing the
ones that are only poor,

00:40:23.570 --> 00:40:27.070
the only ones that
are poorly performing.

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:29.320
There may be some
changes that you

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:35.980
can do to well-performing routes
to improve the overall system

00:40:35.980 --> 00:40:39.340
performance and the
network level performance.

