00:41:35.790 --> 00:41:43.730
So this is the standard
process of decision

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:46.820
making when it comes to new
projects and new proposals,

00:41:46.820 --> 00:41:53.822
service proposals, and changes
to the existing service

00:41:53.822 --> 00:41:57.170
in Toronto Transit Commission.

00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:00.740
This gives you an overview
of different tasks

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:06.170
that are basically done to
start with a set of proposals

00:42:06.170 --> 00:42:12.690
and to make the decision on
which ones to be implemented

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:14.190
and so on and so forth.

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:18.250
So if you look at the
column on the right,

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:21.650
it basically includes
the decision--

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:23.860
it deals mostly with
the decision making

00:42:23.860 --> 00:42:28.400
on the new service proposals.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:35.080
First, you get some
requests from municipalities

00:42:35.080 --> 00:42:38.920
and some suggestions
from the staff

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:42.370
about new service proposals.

00:42:42.370 --> 00:42:50.470
Then, if these proposals are
passing your system guidelines,

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:53.030
then there would be
two possibilities.

00:42:53.030 --> 00:42:57.290
If they are minor costs, they'd
go directly to recommendation.

00:42:57.290 --> 00:42:59.350
And if they are
major costs, then you

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:01.750
need to do a benefit
cost analysis,

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:04.600
and that basically
includes estimation

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:09.400
of ridership and estimation
of costs and benefits.

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:15.150
And then, once you have a better
sense of benefits and costs

00:43:15.150 --> 00:43:20.840
and benefit/cost
measures of the project,

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:24.010
then there will be a
comparative evaluation

00:43:24.010 --> 00:43:28.570
of alternative designs
and alternative proposals.

00:43:28.570 --> 00:43:31.060
At this stage, there
will be another input

00:43:31.060 --> 00:43:35.170
from changes to the
existing system that

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:39.010
comes into the comparative
evaluation, which we will

00:43:39.010 --> 00:43:42.840
get to that branch in a minute.

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:48.610
After these projects get to
the recommendation level,

00:43:48.610 --> 00:43:52.590
the staff makes a
recommendation to the board,

00:43:52.590 --> 00:43:57.360
and then there will be
a review and decision

00:43:57.360 --> 00:44:02.160
about acceptance or rejections
of some of these proposals.

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:04.680
And then there will
be an implementation

00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:07.140
of the successful proposals.

00:44:07.140 --> 00:44:10.842
And then there will
be a probationary time

00:44:10.842 --> 00:44:16.110
to implement the successful
proposals and then to,

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:21.240
after six months, it will get
back to the recommender team

00:44:21.240 --> 00:44:27.510
to see if it would pass
the probationary period.

00:44:27.510 --> 00:44:31.790
On the other hand,
there is a set

00:44:31.790 --> 00:44:35.420
of proposals that are made to
make changes to the existing

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:39.990
service and that basically
comes from two main streams--

00:44:39.990 --> 00:44:45.290
one is a continuous monitoring
of ridership and loads

00:44:45.290 --> 00:44:49.700
and the other one is the
annual route efficiency review.

00:44:49.700 --> 00:44:54.350
And from this, then
the staff actually

00:44:54.350 --> 00:44:58.040
identify service changes
and assess the impacts

00:44:58.040 --> 00:44:59.930
on passengers.

00:44:59.930 --> 00:45:03.260
If the impacts are
minor, it goes directly

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:04.940
and it becomes implemented.

00:45:04.940 --> 00:45:08.560
If impacts are major,
then these changes

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:12.110
become into a form of
a proposal and comes

00:45:12.110 --> 00:45:16.130
to the stream of
comparative analysis

00:45:16.130 --> 00:45:21.200
that would be actually compared
with new service proposals

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:26.071
and follow the same
procedure with that.

00:45:26.071 --> 00:45:26.570
OK.

00:45:26.570 --> 00:45:27.611
Any questions about this?

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:37.150
We'll actually get to
the main two streams

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:42.610
on changes to the
existing service

00:45:42.610 --> 00:45:45.770
in the second next
slide right now.

00:45:45.770 --> 00:45:49.510
So the first slide is
dealing with basically

00:45:49.510 --> 00:45:53.110
the continuous
monitoring of the system

00:45:53.110 --> 00:45:58.330
that Transit Authority
or transit agency staff

00:45:58.330 --> 00:45:59.980
regularly do.

00:45:59.980 --> 00:46:05.170
It's basically, the input
into this kind of process

00:46:05.170 --> 00:46:09.700
involves ridership counts,
regular ridership counts,

00:46:09.700 --> 00:46:13.750
customer communication,
customer complaint records,

00:46:13.750 --> 00:46:16.930
some observations
from staff in terms

00:46:16.930 --> 00:46:18.920
of the performance
of these routes

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:24.250
and for possible
adjustments that

00:46:24.250 --> 00:46:27.790
could be done and then
from operations report.

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:35.290
Then there will be a comparison
of ridership to load standards.

00:46:35.290 --> 00:46:37.600
What we basically
discussed last week

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:41.290
in terms of level of
service measures related

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:48.220
to maximum load will actually
be tested for all the routes.

00:46:48.220 --> 00:46:54.080
And then depending
on the situation,

00:46:54.080 --> 00:47:02.320
if there is available vehicles
and budgets, then the staff

00:47:02.320 --> 00:47:06.390
actually making their
recommendations of changing

00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:09.280
the service, if there is
availability of vehicle

00:47:09.280 --> 00:47:12.120
and budget, there will be
improvement in the service

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:14.280
and increase in
the service level.

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:18.520
And then it will be reviewed for
recommendation, staff approval,

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:23.230
and implementation, and this is
a closed loop that is usually

00:47:23.230 --> 00:47:26.210
done on a regular basis.

00:47:26.210 --> 00:47:28.720
Then there is another
process related

00:47:28.720 --> 00:47:30.490
to the existing
service that deals

00:47:30.490 --> 00:47:38.290
with yearly review of the routes
in terms of route efficiency

00:47:38.290 --> 00:47:39.430
review.

00:47:39.430 --> 00:47:45.070
And basically, you kind
of consider a route

00:47:45.070 --> 00:47:47.990
from a cost and
benefit perspective.

00:47:47.990 --> 00:47:53.740
And on the left, you can see new
riding counts or yearly riding

00:47:53.740 --> 00:47:59.110
counts that's actually are
collected from the study year.

00:47:59.110 --> 00:48:05.170
And then that goes
complemented with the record

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:07.720
of complaints and
customer satisfaction

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:10.690
reports and service regularity.

00:48:10.690 --> 00:48:15.520
And it will be combined with
the financial performance

00:48:15.520 --> 00:48:17.710
and basically the
measure of costs

00:48:17.710 --> 00:48:20.230
that are spent to each route.

00:48:20.230 --> 00:48:28.340
And then it comes to this
joint here with reviewing

00:48:28.340 --> 00:48:29.960
the structure of the route.

00:48:29.960 --> 00:48:32.720
Some of these
routes may be routes

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:37.250
with branches which actually
makes the analysis a little bit

00:48:37.250 --> 00:48:41.500
more difficult,
especially design

00:48:41.500 --> 00:48:46.250
of branching and alignment
of branching, making sure

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:56.070
that the frequency and the
load profiles and maximum loads

00:48:56.070 --> 00:48:59.460
are actually satisfying
the standards

00:48:59.460 --> 00:49:00.840
before and after the joints.

00:49:00.840 --> 00:49:05.490
Because as you may have
already thought about,

00:49:05.490 --> 00:49:11.070
some of-- so, for example,
say Green Line here in Boston,

00:49:11.070 --> 00:49:12.450
in the part that is--

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:26.760
for example, where
you have higher demand

00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:31.780
in the central area, one
of the effective techniques

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:38.470
in design of routes is to
join some of these routes

00:49:38.470 --> 00:49:42.370
into one service to avoid
additional transfers

00:49:42.370 --> 00:49:48.760
and to produce connectivity
to the central area

00:49:48.760 --> 00:49:51.250
without need of a transfer here.

00:49:51.250 --> 00:49:55.240
However what it
actually causes is

00:49:55.240 --> 00:50:01.840
that the demand that you're
collecting from lower density

00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:11.240
suburbs are basically based
on given frequencies here.

00:50:11.240 --> 00:50:14.330
And you set these frequency
based on these demands.

00:50:14.330 --> 00:50:17.750
But when it comes
to the merge points,

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:20.480
the frequency will be
the combined frequency

00:50:20.480 --> 00:50:22.850
and the demand, kind
of crowded situation

00:50:22.850 --> 00:50:24.590
will be the combined situation.

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:28.250
So you need to make sure that
all these standards and all

00:50:28.250 --> 00:50:35.802
the guidelines are holding
for all these branches

00:50:35.802 --> 00:50:36.510
at the same time.

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:41.210
OK.

00:50:41.210 --> 00:50:48.360
And then after that, let me try
to clarify this a little bit.

00:50:48.360 --> 00:50:54.090
For example, considering the--

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:56.190
similar to the
example that we made

00:50:56.190 --> 00:51:04.320
last week related to two
suburbs that are actually

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:07.620
using the transit service.

00:51:11.550 --> 00:51:20.670
So let's say suburb one, suburb
two, and this is downtown area.

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:24.690
If the existing service is a
direct line between suburb one

00:51:24.690 --> 00:51:30.840
to destination and
passengers from suburb two

00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:35.730
basically walk to this
stop to get to destination,

00:51:35.730 --> 00:51:43.680
then assume that the
new proposal of service

00:51:43.680 --> 00:51:56.440
is basically adding one
detour here to serve this.

00:51:56.440 --> 00:51:58.730
Try to clarify
this a little bit.

00:51:58.730 --> 00:52:05.540
For example, considering
similar to the example

00:52:05.540 --> 00:52:13.990
that we made last week
related to two suburbs that

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:21.920
are actually using the
transit service in the--

00:52:21.920 --> 00:52:31.050
so let's say suburb one, suburb
two, and this is downtown area.

00:52:31.050 --> 00:52:35.040
If the existing service is a
direct line between suburb one

00:52:35.040 --> 00:52:41.190
to destination and
passengers from suburb two

00:52:41.190 --> 00:52:46.110
basically walk to this
stop to get to destination,

00:52:46.110 --> 00:52:54.060
then assume that the
new proposal of service

00:52:54.060 --> 00:53:06.690
is basically adding one detour
here to serve this suburb

00:53:06.690 --> 00:53:11.700
two on the way to destination,
then what needs to be done

00:53:11.700 --> 00:53:16.620
is that we need to make sure
that the total generalized cost

00:53:16.620 --> 00:53:19.980
that is computed for all
the passengers from suburb

00:53:19.980 --> 00:53:23.460
one and suburb
two to destination

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:31.080
would be reduced after the
introduction of this detour.

00:53:31.080 --> 00:53:36.540
And then how do we compute
the total generalized cost

00:53:36.540 --> 00:53:39.030
that is experienced
by the passengers?

00:53:39.030 --> 00:53:44.320
There are some equivalent
values that are usually used.

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:47.460
For example, for every
vehicle travel time,

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:52.230
you assume, one in
vehicle travel minute.

00:53:52.230 --> 00:53:55.110
And then for every
minute of waiting time,

00:53:55.110 --> 00:53:57.900
you assume 1.5 or so.

00:53:57.900 --> 00:54:01.440
For every minute of walking
time that is required,

00:54:01.440 --> 00:54:04.170
you consider two minutes
of in-vehicle time.

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:06.130
That's the case
for, for example,

00:54:06.130 --> 00:54:12.006
when you want to measure the
cost of walking from this area

00:54:12.006 --> 00:54:14.300
to the stop.

00:54:14.300 --> 00:54:16.550
And then the cost
of each transfer

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:24.790
is considered to be 10 minutes,
equivalent to 10 minutes.

00:54:24.790 --> 00:54:27.630
Is there any
questions about this?

