00:57:13.546 --> 00:57:21.360
There is techniques involving
the theory of utility

00:57:21.360 --> 00:57:25.720
maximization that
is usually used

00:57:25.720 --> 00:57:31.530
in practice to look at
the actual observed path

00:57:31.530 --> 00:57:33.480
choices the
passengers are making

00:57:33.480 --> 00:57:39.810
and quantify these coefficients.

00:57:39.810 --> 00:57:42.860
AUDIENCE: So what
if you maximize--

00:57:42.860 --> 00:57:45.680
I mean, for that to result in
benefit for customers overall,

00:57:45.680 --> 00:57:47.620
you would have to
increase, for example,

00:57:47.620 --> 00:57:52.660
like headways or frequencies
from part of the trip,

00:57:52.660 --> 00:57:55.650
but then go back to
previous frequency levels?

00:57:58.610 --> 00:58:00.920
NEEMA NASSIR: You
mean, in the merging?

00:58:00.920 --> 00:58:04.940
AUDIENCE: Here, as
part of the transfers.

00:58:04.940 --> 00:58:09.950
It's only way to maximize
the benefit for customers.

00:58:09.950 --> 00:58:11.370
NEEMA NASSIR: Right.

00:58:11.370 --> 00:58:15.930
So the scenario that I
tried to explain here

00:58:15.930 --> 00:58:21.900
was removing this
route and adding

00:58:21.900 --> 00:58:24.990
this layout for the
route and replacing it

00:58:24.990 --> 00:58:28.300
with this alternative.

00:58:28.300 --> 00:58:37.040
So you can keep the same
frequency before and after

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:40.110
and the waiting time
could be kind of the same.

00:58:40.110 --> 00:58:44.370
Or you can alternatively
add additional routes

00:58:44.370 --> 00:58:49.740
and improve the frequency
for other parts of the system

00:58:49.740 --> 00:58:55.260
but make sure that
you're serving the demand

00:58:55.260 --> 00:58:57.210
on the distant suburb.

00:58:57.210 --> 00:59:00.120
AUDIENCE: How do you
compensate the path right here?

00:59:00.120 --> 00:59:01.940
NEEMA NASSIR: This one, right?

00:59:01.940 --> 00:59:02.475
This part?

00:59:02.475 --> 00:59:04.850
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because they're
traveling a longer route.

00:59:08.209 --> 00:59:09.000
NEEMA NASSIR: Yeah.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.820
They basically-- the in-vehicle
time for these people

00:59:11.820 --> 00:59:13.660
will be increased.

00:59:13.660 --> 00:59:15.930
So this is the
measure like the--

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:23.850
after you implement this change,
if you want to and analyze

00:59:23.850 --> 00:59:30.270
the scenario, the in-vehicle
time for traveling from--

00:59:30.270 --> 00:59:41.820
it's usually IVT for S1 to
D for after will be greater

00:59:41.820 --> 00:59:47.810
than IVT for S1 to D, right?

00:59:47.810 --> 00:59:52.190
So in-vehicle time
will be increased.

00:59:52.190 --> 00:59:55.850
However, what's going
to change for passengers

00:59:55.850 --> 01:00:01.520
who are traveling from S2
to D, the walking distance

01:00:01.520 --> 01:00:08.700
is going to decrease, which
has a coefficient of two.

01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:12.320
The in-vehicle time
may increase somehow

01:00:12.320 --> 01:00:15.830
because they are boarding
now at this point,

01:00:15.830 --> 01:00:18.830
but depending on what
frequencies you're designing,

01:00:18.830 --> 01:00:23.900
you can compute the waiting time
and put that into consideration

01:00:23.900 --> 01:00:25.130
and into computations.

01:00:30.140 --> 01:00:32.090
So how are we doing on time?

01:00:34.978 --> 01:00:35.478
OK.

01:00:38.870 --> 01:00:46.560
So Toronto financial
standards and comparisons--

01:00:46.560 --> 01:00:48.630
basically, service
change proposals

01:00:48.630 --> 01:00:54.160
are evaluated according to
customers gained or lost

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:57.180
per dollar spent or saved.

01:00:57.180 --> 01:01:02.130
Again, the benefit that
is imagined for transit

01:01:02.130 --> 01:01:04.470
is in terms of the
number of customers,

01:01:04.470 --> 01:01:07.440
the number of passengers
that are added and are

01:01:07.440 --> 01:01:09.480
using and benefiting
from the service.

01:01:09.480 --> 01:01:13.500
And the cost side is
basically the net cost,

01:01:13.500 --> 01:01:17.870
like the operating
cost minus the revenue.

01:01:17.870 --> 01:01:22.440
And Toronto applies this
for new service proposals

01:01:22.440 --> 01:01:26.685
and possible reduction to the
service and to fare changes.

01:01:31.190 --> 01:01:33.540
Again, the financial
unit actually

01:01:33.540 --> 01:01:36.650
that goes into
these computations

01:01:36.650 --> 01:01:41.750
is the net cost, operating
cost minus the revenue.

01:01:41.750 --> 01:01:44.840
And the threshold that
is used by Toronto

01:01:44.840 --> 01:01:51.530
is 0.23 as the
standard threshold,

01:01:51.530 --> 01:01:55.700
that's 0.23 passengers
per dollar spent.

01:01:55.700 --> 01:01:58.220
So for each dollar
that you're spending

01:01:58.220 --> 01:02:05.490
on the operation
minus the revenue,

01:02:05.490 --> 01:02:10.700
you need to guarantee at least
point 0.23 passengers are

01:02:10.700 --> 01:02:12.135
basically getting served.

01:02:12.135 --> 01:02:14.422
AUDIENCE: That's operating
dollars and passengers.

01:02:17.954 --> 01:02:19.862
It's not a capital expense.

01:02:19.862 --> 01:02:20.932
It's operating.

01:02:20.932 --> 01:02:22.140
NEEMA NASSIR: It's operating.

01:02:22.140 --> 01:02:26.760
Yeah, I think it's operating
cost minus the revenue,

01:02:26.760 --> 01:02:27.820
probably, right.

01:02:27.820 --> 01:02:28.800
AUDIENCE: Yeah, OK.

01:02:32.230 --> 01:02:34.200
NEEMA NASSIR: Right.

01:02:34.200 --> 01:02:38.670
And then services that are
operating below this level,

01:02:38.670 --> 01:02:43.761
we actually get kind of reviewed
in the annual yearly review

01:02:43.761 --> 01:02:44.260
process.

01:02:48.750 --> 01:02:52.910
Again, in terms of
service change process,

01:02:52.910 --> 01:02:57.220
major service changes are
evaluated twice per year.

01:02:57.220 --> 01:03:04.410
They're basically ranked
in the comparative analysis

01:03:04.410 --> 01:03:09.925
and based on their performance
and based on productivity

01:03:09.925 --> 01:03:11.280
of the existing service.

01:03:13.930 --> 01:03:17.710
There is a board in
the Transit Agency

01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:19.900
that makes these decisions.

01:03:19.900 --> 01:03:29.020
Usually, they invite people
from metropolitan transportation

01:03:29.020 --> 01:03:34.930
planning agencies too or higher
level governmental agencies.

01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:37.360
So these boards basically
review the recommendations

01:03:37.360 --> 01:03:41.020
from the staff
and make decisions

01:03:41.020 --> 01:03:44.620
based on their merits.

01:03:44.620 --> 01:03:48.220
The guiding principles
for TransLink

01:03:48.220 --> 01:03:51.070
for Vancouver in service
optimization program,

01:03:51.070 --> 01:03:56.410
is to maintain basic service
for transit-dependent customers,

01:03:56.410 --> 01:04:01.990
like what we discussed
about the existing service

01:04:01.990 --> 01:04:04.870
and how passengers may
actually be dependent.

01:04:04.870 --> 01:04:06.250
And we need to be
careful when we

01:04:06.250 --> 01:04:08.650
want to remove some of
the existing service

01:04:08.650 --> 01:04:12.310
and maintain service that
are strategic for network

01:04:12.310 --> 01:04:14.290
connectivity.

01:04:14.290 --> 01:04:16.150
Sometimes it becomes
a little tricky

01:04:16.150 --> 01:04:21.460
when we look at the routes
individually and do not

01:04:21.460 --> 01:04:24.970
consider their role
and their functionality

01:04:24.970 --> 01:04:28.420
in the performance
at the network level.

01:04:28.420 --> 01:04:32.020
So the guiding
principles of TransLink

01:04:32.020 --> 01:04:36.250
kind of enforce
this concentration.

01:04:36.250 --> 01:04:39.880
And then minimize service
reductions in area

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:45.820
with no transit alternatives,
supporting growing market

01:04:45.820 --> 01:04:50.020
where productivity is
improving, reinvest in service

01:04:50.020 --> 01:04:52.270
to generate higher
revenue ridership,

01:04:52.270 --> 01:04:57.520
and reinvest in service that
supports long-term goals

01:04:57.520 --> 01:05:00.820
and objectives of TransLink.

01:05:00.820 --> 01:05:06.400
So let's open a discussion
now for a few minutes in terms

01:05:06.400 --> 01:05:10.930
of possible critiques
and possible caveats

01:05:10.930 --> 01:05:18.460
of the existing practice
for short-range planning.

